gomodel:SYNGO_746  a      owl:Ontology ;
        rdfs:comment      "Rationale: Conclusion: \"Our study supports the growing consensus that Cplxs (Cplx3 in RBs and Cplx1 and Cplx2 at conventional synapses) act to stabilize fully primed vesicles in a release-ready state and to suppress unregulated Ca2+-dependent spontaneous and asynchronous release of immature vesicles at early stages of the priming process.\"\n\nElectrophysiological recordings in mouse retina tissue analyzing wildtype- and Complexin-3 KO mice. Mouse retinal bipolar cells only express Complexin-3 and are therefore a good synapse to study the function of this protein (it is known that Complexins are partially redundant and can compensate for the loss of one isoform).\n\nThe study demonstrates a loss of phasic release (reduced EPSC amplitude; Fig.1), increase in spontaneous release (mEPSC frequency Fig.2+6) and asynchronous release (Fig. 7). Impaired phasic release was manifested both in a reduced functional RRP and in an increased EPSC latency. The diminished functional RRP likely resulted from the absence of a facilitatory effect of Cplx3 on Ca2+-dependentexocytosis (Fig. 4) rather than from physical vesicle depletion as assessed by electron microscopy (Fig. S1).. Experimental description: Retinas from dark-adapted Cplx3-/-, littermate Cplx3+/+, or C57B6 mice (1-6 months old) (Reim et al., 2009) were isolated..." ;
        lego:modelstate   "production" ;
        dc:contributor    "https://orcid.org/0000-0003-0938-8534" , "https://orcid.org/0000-0002-0755-5899" , "https://orcid.org/0000-0001-7351-8706" , "https://orcid.org/0000-0003-3185-5709" ;
        dc:date           "2017-08-25" ;
        dc:title          "SYNGO_BP_746" ;
        pav:providedBy    "https://syngo.vu.nl" ;
        biolink:in_taxon  "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/NCBITaxon_10090" .

